metadata.name: Sweeping #156
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

metadata.name: Absorbed #199
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF‚Äôs Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT‚Ñ¢). 

MAT‚Ñ¢ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT‚Ñ¢. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed ‚Äì high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and ‚Äúsinusoidal‚Äù noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists‚Äô belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica‚Äôs companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: Flow 2 #67
metadata.description:
This series is a collection of animations based on noise fields and fluid dynamics. The pieces are designed to run continuously, and they produce slowly evolving images that seem to drip, swirl, pulse, and flow. Dense networks of patterns emerge and decay as the pieces evolve. Because of their subtle movement, these works make excellent wall art when run on a display monitor.

Flow 2 is somewhat less chaotic and more meditative than the original. It employs different brushstrokes and a different decay algorithm. I also added a number of new color palettes, now 35 in all.

While these animations are most interesting to view at larger sizes, if your performance begins to suffer just reduce the size of your viewing window.

-spacebar will pause the animation

-return will resume the animation

-r will restart the animation

Flow 2, 2022
-hieroglyphica

metadata.name: Telar #56
metadata.description:
Telar is a study about weaving.

Weaving is one of the oldest crafts in the world. It's been part of our history for almost 30,000 years. 

We are used as species to continuously see patterns generated by millions of binary decisions between colors. These patterns are part of the social DNA of almost every human culture, and their complex aesthetics generated by the most simple inputs are fascinating to me.

This piece, inspired by the mechanism of the Jacquard Loom ‚Äî which is widely considered the first computer ‚Äî uses combinations of colors, series, threading, treadling, and tie-up patterns to generate a unique 360-by-360-thread Telar ("loom" in Spanish). 

The algorithm called telar.js uses the hash to select some colors from preselected patterns and uses the input series to generate a base model with a starting pattern. After that, multiple iterations alter the model appending new tie-ups and modifying the threading or treadling and colors while keeping the design consistent. A resulting matrix containing each intersection then gets drawn on the screen resulting in a high-definition image the viewer can zoom in and see in detail. 

This algorithm takes too many pseudorandom trait values as its inputs that naming them was meaningless, so I would prefer collectors to focus on the subjective aesthetic values of the outputs. Therefore I am hiding the features for this collection.

Press 'S' on your keyboard to save it as a 36 megapixels print. Use the arrow keys to flip between the face and the back of the fabric.

metadata.name: Finding My Way #153
metadata.description:
This piece can be thought as a reflection on the paths we follow while finding our way through life.

Some of us explore more paths, others, less. Often, we find ourselves where we had been before, and we have to start again. Sometimes we take bold steps, sometimes less bold ones. Some paths are filled with love, others, with blues. 
We grow up, and we broaden our paths, or narrow them. 

Or, you can think of this piece as just a bunch of lines, grown progressively using a process similar to Substrate (Jared Tarbell, 2003), modified with a vector field generated with trigonometric functions. 

Random features include the color palette, the number of lines, their width, the scaling of the vector field, and margins.

Some color palettes were inspired by the beautiful plotter works of Iskra Velitchkova.

Original artwork by Roberto Ranon aka Dobleganger aka Doble ¬∑ Made with p5.js ¬∑ Udine, 2021

metadata.name: Textile Bacteria #113
metadata.description:
Telar's code became self-aware and tried to escape. I built a containment unit. "Textile Bacteria" is the result.

--

The piece is based on the 1970's work of the British mathematician John Conway's "Conway's Game of Life" cellular automaton. To avoid bacteria from dying when one of the threads ends up entirely on top of the other the algorithm adds one pseudorandom artificial cross in the weaving feeding the creatures keeping at the same time the weave consistent.

- Left-click to feed dead bacteria.
- Use the arrow keys to flip between the face and the back of the fabric.
- Press 'SPACE' on your keyboard to pause/play. 
- Press 'ENTER' on your keyboard to rewind. 
- Press 'F' on your keyboard to toggle between full-screen and regular view. 
- Press 'S' on your keyboard to save it as a 36 megapixels print.

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #369
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: Tangentum #115
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400
